Yeah.

00:43:29.320 --> 00:43:31.770
We have about five or 10
minutes for questions.

00:43:58.481 --> 00:43:58.980
OK.

00:43:58.980 --> 00:44:00.150
No, I can see that.

00:44:03.130 --> 00:44:07.830
Let me see if I can
explain what I mean.

00:44:07.830 --> 00:44:17.660
The experience, my
experience in life,

00:44:17.660 --> 00:44:22.140
is that there is a
radiant, inner stillness

00:44:22.140 --> 00:44:25.000
and happiness within me.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:31.890
And it's not anything
that I and the people who

00:44:31.890 --> 00:44:38.490
I admire who write
and think about this

00:44:38.490 --> 00:44:39.850
also happen to believe.

00:44:39.850 --> 00:44:42.820
They believe that it's
not anything external.

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:45.010
It's not anything that
we have to acquire.

00:44:45.010 --> 00:44:48.630
It is a case of letting
go to acquire it.

00:44:48.630 --> 00:44:50.625
But to do that we
need to have a focus.

00:44:50.625 --> 00:44:52.810
That was the point about focus.

00:44:52.810 --> 00:44:57.030
So many people in life
don't have a focus.

00:44:57.030 --> 00:44:59.030
They're not this way and
they're not that way.

00:44:59.030 --> 00:45:00.310
And they get this promotion.

00:45:00.310 --> 00:45:02.450
but then they think, is
this really what I want?

00:45:02.450 --> 00:45:04.990
They go from that promotion.

00:45:04.990 --> 00:45:11.020
My experience of being in
schools and a teacher and still

00:45:11.020 --> 00:45:12.905
more ahead for the
last 20 years where

00:45:12.905 --> 00:45:17.200
I come across many parents
is that many have just

00:45:17.200 --> 00:45:20.610
been swept along into jobs
without thinking whether that

00:45:20.610 --> 00:45:21.920
was really what they want.

00:45:21.920 --> 00:45:25.330
So one of things I've
tried to do at schools

00:45:25.330 --> 00:45:29.580
as well as giving them a really
big grounding in what we've

00:45:29.580 --> 00:45:34.770
been talking about in stillness,
and positive psychology,

00:45:34.770 --> 00:45:40.590
is to help them to find out
what they really want to do,

00:45:40.590 --> 00:45:43.370
young people what do you
want to do in your life?

00:45:43.370 --> 00:45:45.080
What do you love about life?

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:49.290
And if you want to
be a carer in life

00:45:49.290 --> 00:45:54.640
and your parents want you
to be a bond trader, well,

00:45:54.640 --> 00:45:56.420
sorry if they were
great parents,

00:45:56.420 --> 00:45:58.540
they'd want you to be
what you want to be.

00:45:58.540 --> 00:46:02.610
And that's why many parents get
it wrong, because for the best

00:46:02.610 --> 00:46:05.870
reason in the world, they
impose their own thoughts.

00:46:05.870 --> 00:46:08.590
So focus is about trying to
find out what your focus is

00:46:08.590 --> 00:46:11.190
and getting in touch with that.

00:46:11.190 --> 00:46:13.760
I think the other example
there would also be you

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:16.990
can see how they too can
be things that we let go of

00:46:16.990 --> 00:46:18.460
and all this.

00:46:18.460 --> 00:46:20.510
I first became really
interested in this

00:46:20.510 --> 00:46:22.870
when I came across somebody
who-- has anyone come

00:46:22.870 --> 00:46:26.020
across Martin Seligman here?

00:46:26.020 --> 00:46:28.950
Very simple, Martin Seligman--
one or two of you have.

00:46:28.950 --> 00:46:35.105
Martin Seligman spent his life
studying depression in America.

00:46:37.890 --> 00:46:41.009
Very well known
and very celebrated

00:46:41.009 --> 00:46:43.050
and one of the things he
learned about depression

00:46:43.050 --> 00:46:48.830
was that people have a sense
of learned helplessness.

00:46:48.830 --> 00:46:50.240
They learn to be helpless.

00:46:50.240 --> 00:46:53.190
They learn to think that they
can't have personal affect,

00:46:53.190 --> 00:46:58.850
that they can't ever get over
their neuroses or psychoses,

00:46:58.850 --> 00:47:02.190
that they'll be
depressed forever.

00:47:02.190 --> 00:47:04.610
It's a learned action.

00:47:04.610 --> 00:47:06.730
But he then realized
that you can actually

00:47:06.730 --> 00:47:10.120
learn optimism also.

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:12.160
And when he was elected
President the American

00:47:12.160 --> 00:47:15.440
Psychological
Association in 1998,

00:47:15.440 --> 00:47:18.640
he made his inaugural
address about why

00:47:18.640 --> 00:47:20.675
is academic psychology,
not just American

00:47:20.675 --> 00:47:22.050
and Britain and
Europe, the world

00:47:22.050 --> 00:47:25.630
over, obsessed by the
abnormal, obsessed

00:47:25.630 --> 00:47:33.990
by OCD and depression and
neuroses and addictions

00:47:33.990 --> 00:47:35.580
and anxieties and fears.

00:47:35.580 --> 00:47:38.180
Where are the studies
looking at the ingredients

00:47:38.180 --> 00:47:39.190
of good organizations?

00:47:39.190 --> 00:47:42.600
So Google is a
great organization.

00:47:42.600 --> 00:47:44.950
And the way the
spaces are organized

00:47:44.950 --> 00:47:49.220
shows how you could
be very imaginative.

00:47:49.220 --> 00:47:51.730
What are the ingredients
of a great relationship?

00:47:51.730 --> 00:47:54.600
So if you have a problem
with your partner, you can go

00:47:54.600 --> 00:47:56.220
and you could talk
to a counselor.

00:47:56.220 --> 00:47:57.746
And the traditional
way of doing it

00:47:57.746 --> 00:48:00.620
is to say, well,
what's going wrong?

00:48:00.620 --> 00:48:03.170
But this way says,
what's going right?

00:48:03.170 --> 00:48:05.990
You know what is going
right in your relationship?

00:48:05.990 --> 00:48:09.350
When are you having a
really good time together?

00:48:09.350 --> 00:48:10.546
Are you having enough sex?

00:48:10.546 --> 00:48:12.170
Are you going out to
the cinema enough?

00:48:12.170 --> 00:48:13.500
Are you having enough fun?

00:48:13.500 --> 00:48:16.120
Are you doing the kind
of things you used to do,

00:48:16.120 --> 00:48:19.090
that you used to really enjoy
them as sacred between you?

00:48:19.090 --> 00:48:20.570
Are you going out
on enough dates?

00:48:20.570 --> 00:48:21.945
By the way, the
recommendation is

00:48:21.945 --> 00:48:24.910
that you have two dates with
your partner every week.

00:48:24.910 --> 00:48:29.500
And these are serious things
that we can take responsibility

00:48:29.500 --> 00:48:33.450
for to make our own lives
happier, recognizing our lives,

00:48:33.450 --> 00:48:36.030
being happy will make other
people's lives happier

00:48:36.030 --> 00:48:36.730
around us.

00:48:36.730 --> 00:48:40.040
So positive psychology as
opposed to traditional,

00:48:40.040 --> 00:48:40.750
negative.

00:48:40.750 --> 00:48:44.140
So much of academic
disciplines are actually

00:48:44.140 --> 00:48:46.400
quite negative in the
way they look at life.

00:48:46.400 --> 00:48:50.080
So that was the kind of genesis
to me of a lot of this work.

00:48:50.080 --> 00:48:53.430
And Seligman's a key figure
in action to happiness,

00:48:53.430 --> 00:48:56.090
or his influence is.

